The Data

The data is on Sakai in the data folder. You will be working with the data in the file called wweCalls. You should use functions within R (e.g., unzip or unz) to unzip it.

Bronze

Step 1

Read all the parsed transcripts and combine all rows in different files together


library(tidyverse)
library(dplyr)

parsed <- list.files(pattern = ".*parse.*csv")
myfiles <- parsed%>%
  lapply(read.csv, stringsAsFactors=F)%>%
  bind_rows

Data cleaning


library(tm)
myfiles$text=str_squish(myfiles$text)
myfiles$text=tolower(myfiles$text)
myfiles$text=gsub("\\$*\\d+\\,*\\%*\\/*","",myfiles$text)
myfiles$text=gsub("\\W"," ",myfiles$text)
myfiles$text=gsub("\\s+", " ",myfiles$text)
myfiles$text=gsub("\\$*\\d+\\,*\\%*\\/*","",myfiles$text)
myfiles$text=removeWords(words = stopwords("en"),myfiles$text)

Data cleaning continue (solve the title inconsistency probelm)


library(data.table)

myfiles<- myfiles%>%
  mutate(title = ifelse(title %like% "*CFO*", "CFO", title),
         title = ifelse(title %like% "*Planning*", "Director of Planning and Analysis",title),
         title = ifelse(title %like% "*Chief Executive Officer*", "CEO",title),
         title = ifelse(title %like% "*CEO*", "CEO",title),
         title = ifelse(title %like% "*Chairman*", "CEO",title),
         title = ifelse(title %like% "Chief Financial Officer", "CFO",title),
         title = ifelse(title %like% "Chief Fiancial Operator", "CFO",title),
         title = ifelse(title %like% "Chief Accounting Officer", "CAO",title),
         title = ifelse(title %like% "VP*", "VP-IR",title),
         title = ifelse(title %like% "- I think it was", NA, title))

# The number of calls of each title.
myfiles2<- myfiles%>%
  filter(title!=is.na(title))%>%

Step 2

Perform sentiment analyses on the texts. Given that these are earnings calls, you will likely want to use Loughran and McDonald’s lexicon. This lexicon can be found in the lexicon package and in the textdata package. You should also explore the various nrc lexicons. Exploring the versions offered in textdata is a good start. Select any of the emotions from the various nrc lexicons (found within textdata) and perform sentiment analyses using that particular emotion. A good approach would be to use the words found within textdata and find them within lexicon.

Below is an example of how you might get data from textdata.


#install.packages("tm")
library(tm)
library(textdata)
library(tidytext)
library(sentimentr)

# get_sentiments("nrc")

# nrcWord <- textdata::lexicon_nrc()

 nrcValues <- lexicon::hash_sentiment_nrc  # -1 or 1

 nrcDominance <- textdata::lexicon_nrc_vad() # Valence, arousal and dominance

 positive<- get_sentiments("nrc")%>%  #The positive words in the lexicon
   filter(sentiment=='positive')

 SentDict <- left_join(positive, nrcDominance, by = c("word"="Word"))

Aggregate sentiment by role within the call

The average sentiment scores for all positions indicate that Research Associates, VP of investors relationship and people with ‘media’ in their title have relatively positive attitude toward clients comparing to CAO, COO, CFO and CEO. This might due to the different functions of each positions. Positions related to marketing require more friendly tone in communication comparing to positions related to management. Also, as there is only one call from CAO and many calls from Analysts, CEO, CFO, and COO, we should take this imbalanced problem into consideration when making decison based on this analysis.


library(sentimentr)

rawsentiment <-sentiment(myfiles1$text, polarity_dt = lexicon::hash_sentiment_nrc)

#Adding title column to rawsentiment dataframe for inner join
rawsentiment <- rawsentiment%>%
  mutate(title = c("Analyst", "CAO", "CEO", "CFO",  "COO", "Director of Planning and Analysis",
                   "IR","Media","Research Associates - Analyst","VP-IR"))

#Inner join 
AvgSentiment <-  inner_join(rawsentiment, myfiles1, by = "title")

AvgSentByWords <- AvgSentiment%>%
  mutate(AvgSent = sentiment/word_count)%>%
  select(title, AvgSent)%>%
  arrange(desc(AvgSent))

From the sentiment scores of people in different positions, we could tell that c-level leaders have higher scores in dominance and valence and lower score in arousal.This illustrates that people in management level genreally use more strong and dominant words in calls. In addition to this, people with financial related titles such as CFO and CAO tend to be less motivated comparing to the directors and vice presidents.


library(tidytext)

tokens <- myfiles1%>%
  unnest_tokens(tbl = ., output = word, input = text)


tokens %>%
  inner_join(SentDict, by= 'word') %>% 
  group_by(title)%>%
  summarize(number = n(), sentSum = sum(Arousal))%>%
  mutate(Arousal = sentSum / number)%>%
  select(title,Arousal)%>%
  arrange(desc(Arousal))
  
tokens1<- tokens %>%
  inner_join(SentDict, by= 'word') %>% 
  group_by(title)%>%  
  summarize(number1 = n(), sentSum1 = sum(Valence)) %>%
  mutate(Valence = sentSum1 / number1)%>%
  select(title,Valence)%>%
  arrange(desc(Valence))

tokens1

tokens2 <- tokens %>%
  inner_join(SentDict, by= 'word') %>% 
  group_by(title)%>%
  summarize(number2 = n(), sentSum2 = sum(Dominance)) %>%
  mutate(Dominance = sentSum2 / number2)%>%
  select(title,Dominance)%>%
  arrange(desc(Dominance))
tokens2

Combing date, closing price and sentiment scores of each individual date together in a dataframe


myfiles2 <- myfiles%>% 
  filter(title!=is.na(title))%>%
  select(text, date)%>%
  mutate(date= as.Date(date,format = "%d-%b-%y"))%>%
  group_by(date)%>%
  summarise(text = paste0(text,collapse = ""),
         text = str_squish(text))

# get the sentiment score of each date
rawsentiment1 <- sentiment(myfiles2$text, polarity_dt = lexicon::hash_sentiment_nrc)

# combine the sentiment score and date together
Sentiment <- cbind.data.frame(myfiles2, rawsentiment1)%>%
  select(date,sentiment)

# Join sentiment DF with trading
# There are only 33 sentiment score, so NA is filled in the empty rows.
trading1 <- left_join(trading, Sentiment, by =c("timestamp"="date"),fill=TRUE)


trading1<- trading1%>%
  select(timestamp,close, sentiment)%>%
  arrange(.,desc(timestamp))

trading1

Based on the sentiment analysis by day and the 10 trading days around each call’s date, people who want to make decision based on call could anticipate an increase of the closing price with more positive words(higher score) in calls and an decrease of the closing price with relatively less positive words(lower score) in calls. However, this is not always the case. Some date ranges below demonstrate an opposite relationship between the closing price and sentiment score as discussed, but these are just the minor cases.This conclusion is limited because of the amount of data and the imbalanced problem in data.


library(ggplot2)
date_mapping <- match(myfiles2$date,trading1$timestamp)

Step 4

There are two calls within the zip file that you did not use for the previous steps – they are not already parsed. If you are able to parse them, incorporate them into the rest of your data and determine if any new information comes to light.

From the ten day closing price around 2016-7-28 and 2016-10-27, higher sentiment score indicates a decrease in the closing price of the following five days. This represents the minor case that I detected in the above analysis. This might challenge the conclusion that higher sentiment score of calls in each date is an indicator of higher closing price in the following days because there are more evidences showing that this is not the case when combing more date into analysis.
